Got it — you’re using **Git Bash on Windows**, so here’s the simplest way to find case-conflicting branches 👍

---

## ✅ Step 1: List all remote branches

Run:

```bash
git ls-remote --heads origin
```

You’ll get output like:

```
abc123  refs/heads/dev
def456  refs/heads/Dev
```

---

## ✅ Step 2: Find case-insensitive duplicates (Git Bash)

Use this command 👇

```bash
git ls-remote --heads origin | awk '{print tolower($2)}' | sort | uniq -d
```

👉 This shows **duplicate branch names ignoring case**

---

## ✅ Step 3: See actual conflicting branches

Now run:

```bash
git ls-remote --heads origin | sort -k2
```

Then manually check for entries like:

```
refs/heads/dev
refs/heads/Dev   ❌ conflict
```

---

## 🔥 Better One-Liner (Shows exact conflicts)

```bash
git ls-remote --heads origin | awk '{print $2}' | sort | awk '{print tolower($0)" "$0}' | sort | awk '{arr[$1]=arr[$1]" " $2} END {for (i in arr) if (split(arr[i],a," ")>1) print arr[i]}'
```

👉 Output will directly show conflicting branches:

```
refs/heads/dev refs/heads/Dev
```

---

## ✅ After Finding Conflicts

Delete the incorrect one:

```bash
git push origin --delete Dev
```

OR rename:

```bash
git branch -m Dev dev-fixed
git push origin dev-fixed
git push origin --delete Dev
```

